# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] The **2004 European Parliament election** was held between 10 and 13 June 2004 in the 25 member states of the European Union, using varying election days according to local custom.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] The electorate did not vote directly for European political parties, but they voted for candidates of national parties to the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] 342 million people were eligible to vote, the second-largest democratic electorate in the world after India.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] It was the biggest transnational direct election in history, and the 10 new member states elected MEPs for the first time.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] The new (6th) Parliament consisted of 732 Members of the European Parliament (MEPs).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] Results showed a general defeat of governing parties and an increase in representatives from eurosceptic parties.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] The balance of power in the Parliament remained the same (largest party EPP-ED, second largest PES) despite the 10 new member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] Following the 2004 enlargement of the European Union which was finalized on 1 May 2004, this was the first European Parliament election to be held in Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] page which appear to have links with Euronat short of full membership.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2004-european-parliament-election] Gibraltar participated as a result of the judgement in Matthews v.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The **2024 European Parliament election** was held in the European Union (EU) between 6 and 9 June 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] It was the tenth parliamentary election since the first direct elections in 1979, and the first European Parliament election after Brexit.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] A total of 720 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) were elected to represent more than 450 million people from 27 member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This election also coincided with a number of other elections in some European Union member states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The European People's Party led by Ursula von der Leyen won the most seats in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The pro-EU centrist, liberal, social democrat and environmentalist parties suffered losses, while anti-EU right-wing populist parties made gains.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The right-wing European Conservatives and Reformists group overtook the centrist Renew Europe group to win the fourth-most seats, while another right-wing group, Patriots for Europe, the successor of Identity and Democracy, won the third-most seats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In addition, a far-right group, Europe of Sovereign Nations, was formed, becoming the smallest group in the Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In total, 187 MEPs (26% of Parliament) belonged to the hard right, which is more members than ever before in history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 18 July 2024, Ursula von der Leyen was re-elected president of the European Commission in a secret ballot by the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The European People's Party, led by Manfred Weber, won the most seats in the European Parliament, but was then unable to secure support from other parties for Weber as candidate for president of the Commission.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] After initial deadlock, the European Council decided to nominate Ursula von der Leyen as a compromise candidate to be the new Commission President, and the European Parliament elected von der Leyen with 383 votes (374 votes needed).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The Commission as a whole was then approved by the European Parliament on 27 November 2019, receiving 461 votes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The 2019 election saw an increase in the turnout, when 50.7% of eligible voters had cast a vote compared with 42.5% of the 2014 election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This was the first time that turnout had increased since the first European Parliament election in 1979.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In 2024, the Eurobarometer data showed that 71% of Europeans said they are likely to vote in June, 10% higher than those who said they would in 2019.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Since the last European-wide election, the right has continued to rise across Europe, remaining, however, split, mainly by the Russian invasion of Ukraine and Russian relations issue.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In 2024, before the European elections, right-wing populist parties hold or share political power in Hungary (Fidesz), Italy (Brothers of Italy), Sweden (Sweden Democrats), Finland (Finns Party), Slovakia (Slovak National Party) and Croatia (Homeland Movement).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The centre-right EPP has "raised eyebrows" among some commentators for its efforts to charm parties in the ECR to create a broad conservative block, which could upset the long-standing status-quo that has seen the EPP share power with the centre-left S&D and the centrist Renew Group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The Qatargate corruption scandal, which began in December 2022, had destabilized the European Parliament following the arrest of several MEPs including Marc Tarabella; Andrea Cozzolino and Eva Kaili who was stripped of her vice presidency.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Following the scandal, the European Parliament revised its rules of procedure and its code of conduct in September 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The European Parliament views Hungary as a "hybrid regime of electoral autocracy" since 2022 and considers Hungary according to Article 7.1 of the Treaty on European Union in clear risk of a serious breach of the Treaty on European Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In January 2024, a majority of European Parliament MEPs voted for a resolution demanding that the EU Council considers that Hungary be stripped of its EU voting rights under Article 7 of the Treaty.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The dates chosen for the elections conflicted with a long weekend in Portugal, where Portugal Day, a national holiday, was celebrated on 10 June, which was expected to suppress turnout.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Despite an attempt by Portuguese leaders to find a compromise, no change was made to the default date of 6–9 June, which required unanimity to be changed.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Elections to the European Parliament are regulated by the Treaty on European Union, Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union, and the Act concerning the election of the members of the European Parliament by direct universal suffrage (the Electoral Act).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The Electoral Act states that the electoral procedure is governed by the national provisions in each member state, subject to the provisions of the act.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Elections are conducted by direct universal suffrage by proportional representation using either a list system or single transferable vote.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The national electoral threshold may not exceed 5% of votes cast.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In June 2018, the Council agreed to change the EU electoral law and to reform old laws from the 1976 Electoral Act as amended in 2002.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] New provisions included a mandatory 2% threshold for countries with more than 35 seats and rules to prevent voters from voting in multiple countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] After the Act was adopted by the Council following consent given by the European Parliament in July 2018, not all member states ratified the Act prior to the 2019 elections, which took place under the old rules.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] As of 2025, the reform has yet to be ratified by Spain; Cyprus and Germany only ratified in 2023/2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 3 May 2022, the European Parliament voted to propose a new electoral law, which would contain provisions for electing 28 seats on transnational lists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] As of 2024, this reform has not been approved by the Council, which must approve it unanimously, meaning the election will be conducted under the 1976 Electoral Act as amended in 2002.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] As a result of Brexit, 27 seats from the British delegation were distributed to other countries in January 2020 (those elected in 2019, but not yet seated took their seats).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The other 46 seats were abolished with the total number of MEPs decreasing from 751 to 705.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] A report in the European Parliament proposed in February 2023 to modify the apportionment in the European Parliament and increase the number of MEPs from 705 to 716 in order to adapt to the development of the population and preserve degressive proportionality.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] It was passed in the plenary in June 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 26 July 2023, the Council reached a preliminary agreement, which would increase the size of the European Parliament to 720 seats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 13 September 2023, the European Parliament consented to this decision, which was adopted by the European Council on 22 September 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In 2014, the candidate of the largest group, Jean-Claude Juncker, was eventually nominated and elected as Commission president.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] European party leaders aimed to reintroduce the system in 2019, with them selecting lead candidates and organizing a televised debate between those candidates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Following this appointment of a Commission president who had not been a Spitzenkandidat, some called for the system to be abandoned, while others called for it to be revived in the 2024 elections.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In 2023, multiple political parties at the European level announced their intentions to nominate a main candidate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The centre-right EPP held its congress in Bucharest on 6–7 March 2024 to elect its presidential candidate and adopt its election programme.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Nominees required the backing of their own member party and not more than two other EPP member parties from EU countries, with nominations closing on February 21.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 19 February 2024, Ursula von der Leyen announced her intention to run, supported by the CDU.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 7 March von der Leyen was elected presidential candidate with 400 votes in favour, 89 against and 10 blank, out of the 737 EPP delegates at the EPP congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Among others, it is believed that the French and Slovenian delegations voted against.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The centre-left PES held its congress in Rome on 2 March.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Nominees required the backing of nine PES full member parties or organisations, with nominations closing on 17 January.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 18 January, the PES announced that the Luxembourgish European Commissioner for Jobs and Social Rights Nicolas Schmit was the sole nominee to meet the nominating requirements.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] He was then nominated on 2 March during the party congress, along with the adoption of the election programme.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The ALDE party held its extraordinary congress in Brussels on 20–21 March 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 7 March 2024, following months of speculation, Estonian Prime Minister Kaja Kallas announced that she had rejected the offer from ALDE to be the party's Spitzenkandidat.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Luxembourg's former Prime Minister Xavier Bettel announced that he is not interested in the post either.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 11 March, the German FDP nominated Marie-Agnes Strack-Zimmermann to become presidential candidate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] She was then elected on March 20 during the party congress, along with the adoption of the election programme.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] During the 8 March 2024 Convention in Florence, the European Democratic Party nominated Sandro Gozi as its lead candidate and approved its election programme.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] During the 2–4 February 2024 congress in Lyon, the European Green Party elected Terry Reintke and Bas Eickhout as its two presidential candidates and adopted its election programme.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Nominees were Bas Eickhout, Elīna Pinto, Terry Reintke, Benedetta Scuderi.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In October 2023, the congress of the European Free Alliance elected Maylis Roßberg and Raül Romeva as its presidential candidates, and adopted its election programme.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] During the 24–25 February 2024 congress in Ljubljana, the PEL elected Walter Baier as its presidential candidate and adopted its election programme.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In a meeting held on 24 February 2024, the European Christian Political Movement appointed party president Valeriu Ghilețchi as its lead candidate for the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] At its General Assembly in Luxembourg in January 2024, the European Pirate Party nominated Marcel Kolaja and Anja Hirschel as lead candidates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 27 November 2023, Volt Europa adopted its European election programme at its General Assembly in Paris.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] During the 6–7 April 2024 campaign launch event in Brussels the party elected German MEP Damian Boeselager and Dutch MEP Sophie in 't Veld as its lead candidates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Regarding which European Parliament group to join after the elections, Boeselager said he was "*open to discussions*" between remaining in Greens/EFA or joining Renew Europe in due course.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] To emphasise its demand for transnational lists, Volt Europa also presented a symbolic transnational list for the election alongside its leading candidates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Immigration was cited by *Politico* as a key issue in elections in several countries, including Austria, Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Denmark, France, Germany, Ireland and Sweden.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Various sources wrote that an increased influence of right-wing and far-right parties in the European Parliament could derail Ukrainian accession, as polling showed low support for EU enlargement in countries where such parties have power.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Exceptions were Poland's Law and Justice supporting Ukrainian accession, and Hungary's Fidesz—a party highly sceptical of Ukraine—being in favour of bids from Serbia and Bosnia and Herzegovina, two countries with governments favourable to Russia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Ursula von der Leyen, the current European Commission president, did not formally announce her intention to stand for a second term until February 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This led to speculation about other potential EPP candidates, such as president of the European Parliament Roberta Metsola.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] However, on 19 February 2024, von der Leyen announced her intention to seek a second term. and on 7 March she was elected European People's Party presidential candidate with 400 votes in favour, 89 against and 10 blank, out of the 737 EPP congressional delegates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In Germany, the coalition government had also agreed to support the spitzenkandidat system, implicitly accepting the prospect of von der Leyen, who within Germany hails from the opposition CDU party, becoming Commission president again, depending on the election results.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Otherwise, the German government coalition agreement grants the right to nominate the next German EU Commissioner to the Greens, provided the Commission president is not from Germany.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In January 2024, Charles Michel announced he would step down early as president of the European Council to run for the European Parliament instead.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This would have meant that European Union leaders would potentially discuss his successor in the summer.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] His mandate had been to set to expire in November 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] For this unanticipated decision Michel was criticised by EU officials and diplomats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] He was criticised by his political ally Sophie in 't Veld who questioned his "credibility".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This would have been the Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán, whose country would be scheduled to take over the rotating presidency of the European Council on 1 July.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 26 January 2024, Michel withdrew his candidacy and thus delayed his departure.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 27 March, the Czech Republic sanctioned the news site *Voice of Europe*, claiming that the site is part of a network for pro-Russian influence.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The following day, Belgian Prime Minister De Croo, referring to the sanctions during a debate in the Belgian parliament, said that Russia had targeted MEPs, but also paid them.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 2 April, the Czech news portal *Denik N* reported, citing several ministers, that there are audio recordings of the German far-right politician Petr Bystron (MP, AfD) that incriminate him of having accepted money.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 12 April, it became known that the Belgian public prosecutor's office is investigating whether European politicians were paid to spread Russian propaganda.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In addition to Bystron, the investigation is also targeting Dutch MEP Marcel de Graaff (FvD) and German MEP Maximilian Krah (AfD).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Ukrainian politician and businessman Viktor Medvedchuk, who is close to Russian President Vladimir Putin, is believed to be the man behind Voice of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Italy's Lega and the Czech SPD backed the position taken by the National Rally, but Vlaams Belang declined to support expulsion of the AfD from the ID group or rule out further cooperation with the AfD, while criticising Krah's remarks.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The Danish People's Party conditioned future cooperation with the AfD on Krah's exclusion from the ID group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The AfD was expelled from the group on 23 May.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] After the European elections, there are often changes or creation of new political groups by the national parties in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This concerns both the new parties that have not yet announced which group they will be part of, and the parties already present in the European Parliament who choose to change group at the beginning of a new legislature.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] According to the Parliament's rules of procedure, a political group requires at least 23 MEPs from at least one-quarter of the Member States (7 out of 27), and a political declaration, setting out the purpose of the group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Several news outlets have speculated on the possibility of a new group guided by the German Bündnis Sahra Wagenknecht party, created in January 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This 'left-conservative' and eurosceptic group could also include La France Insoumise, the Five Star Movement, ANO 2011, Course of Freedom, Direction – Social Democracy, Voice – Social Democracy, the Lithuanian Regions Party, For Stability!, and Together for Catalonia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] In April 2024, Euractiv reported that BSW announced it had the necessary figures to establish the new group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] After the expulsion of the AfD from ID, it is uncertain where its MEPs will be part of a group after the election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 30 May, RTL Hungary reported that MHM and AfD were considering forming a new group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This 'far-right' and eurosceptic group could include also Niki and Republic Movement.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] After Revival was expelled from ID party, the party organized the 'Sofia Declaration' with the Republic Movement, Forum for Democracy, Our Homeland Movement, Alternative for Sweden and the Agricultural Livestock Party of Greece on 12 April 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The first debate was held on Monday, 29 April 2024 from 19:00 to 20:30 CET at the Theater aan het Vrijthof in Maastricht, Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] It was hosted by Studio Europa Maastricht and Politico Europe and was EBU's Eurovision News Exchange distributed the feed to its public service media network of members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] An initiative of Maastricht University, it was the third edition of the so-called "Maastrich Debate" All ten registered European political parties were invited to the debate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The debate questions focused on three main themes: climate change, foreign and security policy, and EU democracy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] During the debate, Ursula von der Leyen indicated she would be open to a deal with the European Conservatives and Reformists group after the election saying that the collaboration "depends very much on how the composition of the Parliament is, and who is in what group".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The second debate was held on Tuesday, 21 May 2024 from 17:00 to 18:15 in Brussels, Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] It was hosted by the think tank Bruegel and the Financial Times.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The debate questions focused on economic policy in the EU.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The third debate was held on Thursday, 23 May 2024 from 15:00 to 17:00 CET at the European Parliament in Brussels, Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] It was hosted by the European Broadcasting Union together with the European Parliament and it was broadcast on public service media channels and online platforms members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The debate took place in English, with interpretation into all 24 official EU languages and International Sign Language.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] It was the third edition of the so-called "Eurovision Debate".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Invitations to the debate were sent by the EBU to the ten recognised European Political parties, with only one lead candidate allowed to be nominated from each of the seven Political groups of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] On 7 May, EBU announced the candidates for the debate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Two parties, the ECR and ID, were considered by EBU not eligible to take part in the debate, since they have not nominated lead candidates for the Presidency of the European Commission and.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] The debate questions focused on six main topics: Economy and Jobs, Defence and Security, Climate and Environment, Democracy and Leadership, Migration and Borders, Innovation and Technology.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Several voting advice applications at the European level have been developed to help voters choose their candidates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Some of these applications could collect user data for research or commercial purpose.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Europe Elects, Der Föderalist and Politico Europe have been presenting seat projections throughout the legislative period.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Other institutes started presenting data during the election campaign.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] All projections make their national-level data transparent, except Politico Europe, which only presents aggregate EU-level data.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Europe Elects has been presenting popular vote projections throughout the legislative period.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] About 357 million people were eligible to vote in 27 countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Of those, around 182 million people voted.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This represents 51.05% of the total eligible voters, the highest percentage of voter turnout since 1994.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] Affiliation to the parties at the time of the election on 6–9 June 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p01] This shows the composition of the European Parliament at the constitutive session.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Before all results were declared, President of France Emmanuel Macron announced the dissolution of the French National Assembly, calling a snap election on 30 June.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] After the election, the political groups of the European Parliament reconstitute themselves and recruit new members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] The first plenary session of the European Parliament was held on 16–19 July.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 18 June 2024, Hungary's Christian Democratic People's Party (KDNP) officially left the European People's Party, in response to the group's decision to admit the Tisza Party (TISZA), also from Hungary, in their ranks.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Elected MEPs from the Netherlands' Farmer–Citizen Movement (BBB) and New Social Contract (NSC), Czech Republic's Mayors and Independents (STAN), Denmark's Liberal Alliance (LA) and Germany's Family Party also submitted requests to join the EPP Group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 19 June 2024, the European Conservatives and Reformists group announced in an official press release that elected MEPs from Romania's Alliance for the Union of Romanians (AUR), as well as former members of France's Reconquête (including Marion Maréchal), had joined the group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] As a result, the ECR became the third-largest faction in the European Parliament, overtaking Renew Europe in the process.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] However, on 5 July, Spain's Vox announced their intention to leave the ECR, in order to join the new Patriots for Europe alliance; as a result, the group's membership dropped to 78 MEPs, just one ahead of Renew.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] In June 2024, it was reported that five elected MEPs from Volt Europa, two of whom from the Netherlands and three from Germany, had begun negotiations both with Renew Europe and the Greens/EFA to join their respective ranks on a stable basis.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On June 24, Volt officially announced that 87% of the party's members had voted in favour of joining the Greens/EFA group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 21 June 2024, Czech Republic's ANO 2011 announced their decision to unilaterally withdraw from the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party, as well as Renew Europe, due to "different positions" on the European Green Deal and the EU's migration policy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 2 July, Irish MEP Michael McNamara, who had been elected as an independent candidate, officially became a member of Renew.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Despite initial concerns, mainly related to the M5S's past alliances with the UK Independence Party in the Eighth European Parliament, and Lega during the First Conte government, the group officially admitted the party on 4 July.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] In the process, the M5S became the second-most-represented party within the GUE/NGL group, behind only France's La France Insoumise.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Following the announcement of the new Patriots for Europe alliance, Identity and Democracy saw several member parties leave the formation, or express interest in doing so, with examples including Portugal's Chega, France's National Rally and Italy's Lega.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Following the departure of MEPs from several key member parties, the ID group could no longer form a political group in the EU Parliament, which has a minimum requirement of members from at least seven member nations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] According to anonymous ID members, the whole group could eventually get merged into Patriots for Europe, as part of negotiations supervised by the leader of the National Rally, Marine Le Pen.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 8 July 2024, the group officially disbanded, following the establishment of the PfE group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] As a result, the FPÖ would complete a switch from the Identity and Democracy group; on the other hand, ANO 2011 had left Renew Europe a week before the announcement, while MEPs from Fidesz were part of Non-Inscrits since 2021, when the party had left the European People's Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Portugal's Chega officially entered the alliance on 2 July, while Italy's Lega also publicly expressed interest in joining the new group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 5 July, Spain's Vox announced their intention to enter Patriots for Europe, after leaving the ECR group, with Netherlands' Party for Freedom, previously in the ID group, following suit.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] The following day, both Denmark's Danish People's Party (DF) and Belgium's Vlaams Belang switched from ID to the new group; as a result, Patriots for Europe met the EU Parliament's minimum threshold for formal recognition.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] An MEP from the DF party, Anders Vistisen, stated that they agreed to join the alliance upon the condition that each national member would be allowed to pursue their own foreign policy, including on matters such as the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 7 July, the President of France's National Rally (RN), Jordan Bardella, confirmed the party's intention to switch from ID to Patriots for Europe; as a result, the RN became the biggest delegation within the alliance, having elected 30 MEPs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Bardella was appointed as the president of Patriots for Europe, while Vistisen was nominated as their chief whip.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 10 July, It was reported that the MEPs from a branch of Poland's Confederation, National Movement, had expressed an interest in joining the PfE group, which was neither confirmed nor denied by Patriots.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] If the party were to join, it would confirm a split within Confederation's other factions in the EU, New Hope and Confederation of the Polish Crown.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] In June 2024, it was reported that Germany's Alternative for Germany (AfD) party, which had been expelled from Identity and Democracy before the election, was holding talks with other far-right parties for the creation of a new parliamentary group, tentatively named "The Sovereignists".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] According to reports, the group could also include Poland's Confederation, Bulgaria's Revival, Spain's Se Acabó La Fiesta (SALF), Romania's S.O.S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Romania, Slovakia's Republic Movement (Republika), France's Reconquête, Hungary's Our Homeland Movement, Greece's Niki and Czech Republic's Freedom and Direct Democracy (SPD).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 10 July, it was reported that a new parliamentary group, named Europe of Sovereign Nations (ESN), had officially formed, having met the minimum requirements to get formal recognition within the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] René Aust (AfD) and Stanisław Tyszka (NN) were elected co-chairpersons of the parliamentary group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Members from Spain's SALF and Greece's Niki were initially expected to also join ESN, but withdrew at the last minute.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] Three MEPs, Maximilian Krah (from Germany's AfD), Braun and Milan Mazurek (from Slovakia's Republika) were all reportedly excluded from joining the group, due to the anti-semitic and Holocaust-denying nature of their previous public statements.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] The co-leader of AfD, Alice Weidel, commented and said that "no anti-semites should have a place in a potential group with [her] party." Despite previous speculations, Romania's S.O.S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/2024-european-parliament-election-p02] On 18 July 2024, Ursula von der Leyen was re-elected president of the European Commission in a secret ballot, with 401 votes in favour, 284 against, and 22 cast blank or invalid votes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The resultant theory was challenged and refined several times in the decades following its original publication in 1971.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] A significant reappraisal was published in the 1985 essay "Justice as Fairness" and the 2001 book *Justice as Fairness: A Restatement* in which Rawls further developed his two central principles for his discussion of justice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Together, they assert that society should be structured to provide the greatest possible degree of liberty to its members, limited only by the principle that one individual's liberty must not infringe upon the liberty of others.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Secondly, inequalities – either social or economic – are only to be allowed if the worst off will be better off than they might be under an equal distribution.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Finally, if an inequality is to be justified on the grounds of its benefits, it must not create additional barriers for those without resources to access positions of power, such as public office.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] In *A Theory of Justice,* Rawls argues for a principled reconciliation of liberty and equality that is meant to apply to the basic structure of a well-ordered society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Central to this effort is an account of the circumstances of justice, inspired by David Hume, and a fair choice situation for parties facing such circumstances, similar to some of Immanuel Kant's views.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Principles of justice are sought to guide the conduct of the parties.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] These parties are recognized to face moderate scarcity, and they are neither naturally altruistic nor purely egoistic.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] They have ends which they seek to advance but prefer to advance them through cooperation with others on mutually acceptable terms.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls offers a model of a fair choice situation (the original position with its veil of ignorance) within which parties would hypothetically choose mutually acceptable principles of justice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Under such constraints, Rawls believes that parties would find his favoured principles of justice to be especially attractive, winning out over varied alternatives, including utilitarian and right-wing libertarian accounts.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls belongs to the social contract tradition, although he takes a different view from that of previous thinkers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Specifically, Rawls develops what he claims are principles of justice through the use of an artificial device or thought experiment he calls the *Original position*; in which, everyone decides principles of justice from behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] [N]o one knows his place in society, his class position or social status, nor does anyone know his fortune in the distribution of natural assets and abilities, his intelligence, strength, and the like.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] I shall even assume that the parties do not know their conceptions of the good or their special psychological propensities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The principles of justice are chosen behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] They are the principles that rational and free persons concerned to further their own interests would accept in an initial position of equality as defining the fundamentals of the terms of their association.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] If an individual does not know how he will end up in his own conceived society, he is likely not going to privilege any one class of people, but rather develop a scheme of justice that treats all fairly.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] In particular, Rawls claims that those in the *Original Position* would adopt two principles, the second of which is a maximin strategy which would maximize the prospects of the least well-off.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls bases his *Original Position* on a "thin theory of the good" which he says "explains the rationality underlying choice of principles in the Original Position".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] A full theory of the good follows after we derive principles from the original position.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls claims that the parties in the original position would adopt two such principles, which would then govern the assignment of rights and duties and regulate the distribution of social and economic advantages across society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The difference principle permits inequalities in the distribution of goods only if those inequalities benefit the worst-off members of society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls believes that this principle would be a rational choice for the representatives in the original position for the following reason: Each member of society has an equal claim on their society's goods.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Natural attributes should not affect this claim, so the basic right of any individual, before further considerations are taken into account, must be to an equal share in material wealth.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] What, then, could justify unequal distribution?
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls argues that inequality is acceptable only if it is to the advantage of those who are worst-off.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The agreement that stems from the original position is both *hypothetical* and *ahistorical*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] It is hypothetical in the sense that the principles to be derived are what the parties would, under certain legitimating conditions, agree to, not what they have agreed to.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls seeks to use an argument that the principles of justice are what *would* be agreed upon if people were in the hypothetical situation of the original position and that those principles have moral weight as a result of that.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] It is ahistorical in the sense that it is not supposed that the agreement has ever been, or indeed could ever have been, derived in the real world outside of carefully limited experimental exercises.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls modifies and develops the principles of justice throughout his book.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle is often called the *greatest equal liberty principle*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls orders the principles of justice lexically, as follows: **1**, **2b**, **2a**.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* takes priority, followed by the *equal opportunity principle* and finally the *difference principle*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle must be satisfied before 2b, and 2b must be satisfied before 2a.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* is mainly concerned with the distribution of rights and liberties.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] His position is at least in some sense egalitarian, with a provision that inequalities are allowed when they benefit the least advantaged.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] An important consequence of Rawls' view is that inequalities can actually be just, as long as they are to the benefit of the least well off.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] His argument for this position rests heavily on the claim that morally arbitrary factors (for example, the family one is born into) should not determine one's life chances or opportunities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Further, the just savings principle requires that some sort of material respect is left for future generations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Although Rawls is ambiguous about what this means, it can generally be understood as "a contribution to those coming later".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The stipulation in 2b is lexically prior to that in 2a.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] In 1972, *A Theory of Justice* was reviewed in *The New York Times Book Review* by Marshall Cohen, who described the work as "magisterial," and suggested that Rawls' use of the techniques of analytic philosophy made the book the "most formidable" defense of the social contract tradition to date.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Michael Sandel criticized Rawls in *Liberalism and the Limits of Justice* (1982), arguing that Rawls encourages people to think about justice while divorced from the values and aspirations that define who they are as persons and that allow people to determine what justice is.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Susan Moller Okin wrote in *Justice, Gender, and the Family* (1989) that Rawls had provided "the most influential of all twentieth-century theories of justice", but criticized him for failing to account for the injustices and hierarchies embedded in familial relations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] In his book *Black Rights / White Wrongs*, philosopher Charles W.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Mills critiques the underlying assumptions of Rawls’s work as inherently white, and thus subject to glaring blind spots.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] The economist Amartya Sen has raised concerns over Rawls' emphasis on primary social goods, arguing in *Inequality Reexamined* (1992) that we should attend not only to the distribution of primary goods, but also how effectively people are able to use those goods to pursue their ends.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Norman Daniels has wondered why health care should not be treated as a primary good, and some of his subsequent work has addressed this question, arguing for a right to health care within a broadly Rawlsian framework.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Sen critiques and attempts to revitalize *A Theory of Justice* in *The Idea of Justice* (2009).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] He credits Rawls for revitalizing the interest in the ideas of what justice means and the stress put on fairness, objectivity, equality of opportunity, removal of poverty, and freedom.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] However, Sen, as part of his general critique of the contractarian tradition, states that ideas about a perfectly just world do not help redress actual existing inequality.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Sen faults Rawls for overemphasizing institutions as guarantors of justice and not considering the effects of human behaviour on the institutions' ability to maintain a just society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Sen believes Rawls understates the difficulty in getting everyone in society to adhere to the norms of a just society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] He also claims that Rawls' position that there be only one possible outcome of the reflective equilibrium behind the veil of ignorance is misguided.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] In contrast to Rawls, Sen believes that multiple conflicting, yet just, principles may arise and that this undermines the multistep processes that Rawls laid out as leading to a perfectly just society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] Cohen argued that Rawls's principles of justice are influenced by assumptions about social institutions and human behaviour.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-theory-of-justice] He maintained that a theory of justice should identify principles that are fundamentally just independently of practical considerations, and therefore contended that Rawls's account was not a theory of justice in the strict sense.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In this essay, Wollstonecraft refutes those educational and political theorists of the eighteenth century who did not believe women should receive a full education.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She argues that women ought to have an education commensurate with their position in society, claiming that women are essential to the nation because they educate its children and because they could be "companions" to their husbands, rather than mere wives.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Instead of viewing women as ornaments to society or property to be traded in marriage, Wollstonecraft maintains that they are human beings deserving of the same fundamental rights as men.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft specifically calls for equality between the sexes in particular areas of life, especially moral responsibility and educational access.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Uncertainty regarding whether she believed women should have full voting rights or other political rights make it difficult to classify Wollstonecraft definitively as a modern feminist; furthermore, the word *feminist* did not emerge until decades after her death.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] A spiritual sequel to Wollstonecraft's *A Vindication of the Rights of Men* (1790), *Rights of Woman* was inspired after she read Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-Périgord's 1791 report to the National Assembly in revolutionary France, which stated that women should only receive a domestic education.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] From her reaction to this specific event, she launched a broad attack against double standards, indicting men for encouraging women to indulge in excessive emotion.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft hurried to complete the work in direct response to ongoing events; she intended to write a more thoughtful second volume but died before completing it.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The *Rights of Woman* was generally received well when it was first published in 1792.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The modern assumption that it was unfavourably received is a misconception.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In fact, Wollstonecraft was reviled only after details emerged of her personal life after her death, based on the publication of her husband William Godwin's *Memoirs of the Author of A Vindication of the Rights of Woman* (1798).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Sunstein called *Rights of Woman* "perhaps the most original book of [Wollstonecraft's] century".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft's work had a significant impact on advocates for women's rights in the nineteenth century, particularly the 1848 Seneca Falls Convention which produced the Declaration of Sentiments, laying out the aims of the women's suffrage movement in the United States.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] When Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-Périgord presented his *Rapport sur l'instruction publique* (1791) to the National Assembly in France, Wollstonecraft was galvanized to respond.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The *Rights of Woman* is an extension of Wollstonecraft's arguments in the *Rights of Men*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In the *Rights of Men*, as the title suggests, she is concerned with the rights of particular men (eighteenth-century British men) while in the *Rights of Woman*, she is concerned with the rights afforded to "woman", an abstract category.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She does not isolate her argument to eighteenth-century women or British women.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The first chapter of the *Rights of Woman* addresses the issue of natural rights and asks who has those inalienable rights and on what grounds.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She answers that since natural rights are given by God, for one segment of society to deny them to another segment is a sin.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] *The Rights of Woman* thus engages not only specific events in France and in Britain but also larger questions being raised by political philosophers such as John Locke and Jean-Jacques Rousseau.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The *Rights of Woman* is a long (almost 87,000 words) essay that introduces all of its major topics in the opening chapters and then repeatedly returns to them, each time from a different point of view.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] It also adopts a hybrid tone that combines rational argument with the fervent rhetoric of sensibility.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft did not employ the formal argumentation or logical prose style common to eighteenth-century philosophical writing.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Hysteria was once seen as a physical phenomenon – physicians and anatomists believed that the more "sensitive" people's "nerves", the more emotionally affected they would be by their surroundings.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Since women were thought to have keener nerves than men, it was believed that women were more emotional than men.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The emotional excess associated with sensibility also theoretically produced an ethic of compassion: those with sensibility could easily sympathise with people in pain.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Thus historians have credited the discourse of sensibility and those who promoted it with the increased humanitarian efforts, such as the movement to abolish the slave trade.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] But sensibility also paralysed those who had too much of it; as scholar G.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Barker-Benfield explains, "an innate refinement of nerves was also identifiable with greater suffering, with weakness, and a susceptibility to disorder".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] By the time Wollstonecraft was writing the *Rights of Woman*, sensibility had already been under sustained attack for a number of years.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Furthermore, as Janet Todd, another scholar of sensibility, argues, "to many in Britain the cult of sensibility seemed to have feminized the nation, given women undue prominence, and emasculated men".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] One of Wollstonecraft's central arguments in the *Rights of Woman* is that women should be educated in a rational manner to give them the opportunity to contribute to society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In the eighteenth century, it was often assumed by educational philosophers and conduct book writers, who wrote what one might think of as early self-help books, that women were incapable of rational or abstract thought.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Women, it was believed, were too susceptible to sensibility and too fragile to be able to think clearly.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft, along with other female reformers such as Catharine Macaulay and Hester Chapone, maintained that women were indeed capable of rational thought and deserved to be educated.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She argued this point in her own conduct book, *Thoughts on the Education of Daughters* (1787), in her children's book, *Original Stories from Real Life* (1788), as well as in the *Rights of Woman*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She attributes the problem of uneducated women to men and "a false system of education, gathered from the books written on this subject by men who [consider] females rather as women than human creatures".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Women are capable of rationality; it only appears that they are not, because men have refused to educate them and encouraged them to be frivolous (Wollstonecraft describes silly women as "spaniels" and "toys").
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft attacks conduct book writers such as James Fordyce and John Gregory as well as educational philosophers such as Jean-Jacques Rousseau who argue that a woman does not need a rational education.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wives could be the rational "companions" of their husbands and even pursue careers should they so choose: "women might certainly study the art of healing, and be physicians as well as nurses.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] And midwifery, decency seems to allot to them ... they might, also, study politics ...
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For Wollstonecraft, "the most perfect education" is "an exercise of the understanding as is best calculated to strengthen the body and form the heart.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Or, in other words, to enable the individual to attach such habits of virtue as will render it independent." In addition to her broad philosophical arguments, Wollstonecraft lays out a specific plan for national education to counter Talleyrand's.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In Chapter 12, "On National Education", she proposes that children be sent to free day schools as well as given some education at home "to inspire a love of home and domestic pleasures".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She also maintains that schooling should be co-educational, contending that men and women, whose marriages are "the cement of society", should be "educated after the same model".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] It is debatable to what extent the *Rights of Woman* is a feminist text; because the definitions of *feminist* vary, different scholars have come to different conclusions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The words *feminist* and *feminism* were not coined until the 1890s, and there was no feminist movement to speak of during Wollstonecraft's lifetime.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] *Rights of Woman* is often considered the source or original, "the ur-document of modern liberal feminism".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In the *Rights of Woman*, Wollstonecraft does not make the claim for gender equality using the same arguments or the same language that late nineteenth- and twentieth-century feminists later would.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For instance, rather than unequivocally stating that men and women are equal, Wollstonecraft contends that men and women are equal in the eyes of God, which means that they are both subject to the same moral law.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For Wollstonecraft, men and women are equal in the most important areas of life.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] While such an idea may not seem revolutionary to twenty-first-century readers, its implications were revolutionary during the eighteenth century.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For example, it implied that both men and women – not just women – should be modest and respect the sanctity of marriage.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft's argument exposed the sexual double standard of the late eighteenth century and demanded that men adhere to the same virtues demanded of women.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] However, Wollstonecraft's arguments for equality stand in contrast to her statements respecting the superiority of masculine strength and valour.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft calls on men, rather than women, to initiate the social and political changes she outlines in the *Rights of Woman*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Because women are uneducated, they cannot alter their own situation – men must come to their aid.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft's last novel, *Maria: or, The Wrongs of Woman* (1798), the fictionalized sequel to the *Rights of Woman*, is usually considered her most radical feminist work.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] One of Wollstonecraft's most scathing criticisms in the *Rights of Woman* is against false and excessive sensibility, particularly in women.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She argues that women who succumb to sensibility are "blown about by every momentary gust of feeling"; because these women are "the prey of their senses", they cannot think rationally.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Not only do they do harm to themselves but they also do harm to all of civilization: these are not women who can refine civilization – these are women who will destroy it.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] But reason and feeling are not independent for Wollstonecraft; rather, she believes that they should inform each other.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For Wollstonecraft the passions underpin all reason.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] This was a theme that she would return to throughout her career, but particularly in her novels *Mary: A Fiction* (1788) and *Maria: or, The Wrongs of Woman*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For the eighteenth-century Scottish philosopher David Hume, reason is dominated by the passions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] He held that passions rather than reason govern human behaviour, famously proclaiming in *A Treatise of Human Nature* that "Reason is, and ought only to be the slave of the passions".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] As part of her argument that women should not be overly influenced by their feelings and emotions, Wollstonecraft emphasises that they should not be constrained by or made slaves to their bodies or their sexual feelings.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] This particular argument has led many modern feminists to suggest that Wollstonecraft intentionally avoids granting women any sexual desire.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Cora Kaplan argues that the "negative and prescriptive assault on female sexuality" is a leitmotif of the *Rights of Woman*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For example, Wollstonecraft advises her readers to "calmly let passion subside into friendship" in the ideal companionate marriage (that is, in the ideal of a love-based marriage that was developing at the time).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] It would be better, she writes, when "two virtuous young people marry ... if some circumstances checked their passion".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] According to Wollstonecraft, "love and friendship cannot subsist in the same bosom".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] As Mary Poovey explains, "Wollstonecraft betrays her fear that female desire might in fact court man's lascivious and degrading attentions, that the subordinate position women have been given might even be deserved.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Until women can transcend their fleshly desires and fleshly forms, they will be hostage to the body." If women are not interested in sexuality, they cannot be dominated by men.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft worries that women are consumed with "romantic wavering", that is, they are interested only in satisfying their lusts.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Because the *Rights of Woman* eliminates sexuality from a woman's life, Kaplan contends, it "expresses a violent antagonism to the sexual" while at the same time "exaggerat[ing] the importance of the sensual in the everyday life of women".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft was so determined to wipe sexuality from her picture of the ideal woman that she ended up foregrounding it by insisting upon its absence.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Claudia Johnson, a prominent Wollstonecraft scholar, has called the *Rights of Woman* "a republican manifesto".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Johnson contends that Wollstonecraft is hearkening back to the Commonwealth tradition of the seventeenth century and attempting to reestablish a republican ethos.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In Wollstonecraft's version, there would be strong, but separate, masculine and feminine roles for citizens.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] According to Johnson, Wollstonecraft "denounces the collapse of proper sexual distinction as the leading feature of her age, and as the grievous consequence of sentimentality itself.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The problem undermining society in her view is feminized men".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] If men feel free to adopt both the masculine position and the sentimental feminine position, she argues, women have no position open to them in society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Johnson therefore sees Wollstonecraft as a critic, in both the *Rights of Men* and the *Rights of Woman*, of the "masculinization of sensitivity" in such works as Edmund Burke's *Reflections on the Revolution in France*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In the *Rights of Woman* Wollstonecraft adheres to a version of republicanism that includes a belief in the eventual overthrow of all titles, including the monarchy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She also suggests that all men and women should be represented in government.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] But the bulk of her "political criticism", as Chris Jones, a Wollstonecraft scholar, explains, "is couched predominantly in terms of morality".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Her definition of virtue focuses on the individual's happiness rather than, for example, the good of society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] This is reflected in her explanation of natural rights.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Because rights ultimately proceed from God, Wollstonecraft maintains that there are duties, tied to those rights, incumbent upon each and every person.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For Wollstonecraft, the individual is taught republicanism and benevolence within the family; domestic relations and familial ties are crucial to her understanding of social cohesion and patriotism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In many ways the *Rights of Woman* is inflected by a bourgeois view of the world, as is its direct predecessor the *Rights of Men*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft addresses her text to the middle class, which she calls the "most natural state".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She also frequently praises modesty and industry, virtues which, at the time, were associated with the middle class.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] From her position as a middle-class writer arguing for a middle-class ethos, Wollstonecraft also attacks the wealthy, criticizing them using the same arguments she employs against women.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] But Wollstonecraft's criticisms of the wealthy do not necessarily reflect a concomitant sympathy for the poor.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In attempting to navigate the cultural expectations of female writers and the generic conventions of political and philosophical discourse, Wollstonecraft, as she does throughout her *oeuvre*, constructs a unique blend of masculine and feminine styles in the *Rights of Woman*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She uses the language of philosophy, referring to her work as a "treatise" with "arguments" and "principles".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] However, Wollstonecraft also uses a personal tone, employing "I" and "you", dashes and exclamation marks, and autobiographical references to create a distinctly feminine voice in the text.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The *Rights of Woman* further hybridizes its genre by weaving together elements of the conduct book, the short essay, and the novel, genres often associated with women, while at the same time claiming that these genres could be used to discuss philosophical topics such as rights.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Although Wollstonecraft argues against excessive sensibility, the rhetoric of the *Rights of Woman* is at times heated and attempts to provoke the reader.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Many of the most emotional comments in the book are directed at Rousseau.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] In her efforts to vividly describe the condition of women within society, Wollstonecraft employs several different analogies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She often compares women to slaves, arguing that their ignorance and powerlessness places them in that position.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] But at the same time, she also compares them to "capricious tyrants" who use cunning and deceit to manipulate the men around them.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] At one point, she reasons that a woman can become either a slave or tyrant, which she describes as two sides of the same coin.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft also compares women to soldiers; like military men, they are valued only for their appearance and obedience.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] And like the rich, women's "softness" has "debased mankind".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft was forced to write the *Rights of Woman* hurriedly to respond to Talleyrand and ongoing events.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Upon completing the work, she wrote to her friend William Roscoe: "I am dissatisfied with myself for not having done justice to the subject ...
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Do not suspect me of false modesty – I mean to say that had I allowed myself more time I could have written a better book, in every sense of the word ...
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] She changed some of her statements regarding female and male difference to reflect a greater equality between the sexes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft never wrote the second part to the *Rights of Woman,* although William Godwin published her "Hints", which were "chiefly designed to have been incorporated in the second part of the *Vindication of the Rights of Woman*", in the posthumous collection of her works.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] However, she did begin writing the novel *Maria: or, The Wrongs of Woman*, which most scholars consider a fictionalized sequel to the *Rights of Woman*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] It was unfinished at her death and also included in the *Posthumous Works* published by Godwin.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] When it was first published in 1792, the *Rights of Woman* was reviewed favourably by the *Analytical Review*, the *General Magazine*, the *Literary Magazine*, *New York Magazine*, and the *Monthly Review*, although the mistaken assumption persists that *Rights of Woman* received hostile reviews.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] It was almost immediately released in a second edition in 1792, several American editions appeared, and it was translated into French.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Taylor writes that "it was an immediate success".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Moreover, other writers such as Mary Hays and Mary Robinson specifically alluded to Wollstonecraft's text in their own works.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Hays cited the *Rights of Woman* in her novel *Memoirs of Emma Courtney* (1796) and modelled her female characters after Wollstonecraft's ideal woman.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Although female conservatives such as Hannah More excoriated Wollstonecraft personally, they actually shared many of the same values.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] As the scholar Anne Mellor has shown, both More and Wollstonecraft wanted a society founded on "Christian virtues of rational benevolence, honesty, personal virtue, the fulfillment of social duty, thrift, sobriety, and hard work".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] During the early 1790s, many writers within British society were engaged in an intense debate regarding the position of women in society.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] For example, the respected poet and essayist Anna Laetitia Barbauld and Wollstonecraft sparred back and forth; Barbauld published several poems responding to Wollstonecraft's work and Wollstonecraft commented on them in footnotes to the *Rights of Woman*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The work also provoked outright hostility.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The bluestocking Elizabeth Carter was unimpressed with the work.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Thomas Taylor, the Neoplatonist translator who had been a landlord to the Wollstonecraft family in the late 1770s, swiftly wrote a satire called *A Vindication of the Rights of Brutes*: if women have rights, why not animals too?
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] After Wollstonecraft died in 1797, her husband William Godwin published his *Memoirs of the Author of A Vindication of the Rights of Woman* (1798).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] He revealed much about her private life that had previously not been known to the public: her illegitimate child, her love affairs, and her attempts at suicide.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] While Godwin believed he was portraying his wife with love, sincerity, and compassion, contemporary readers were shocked by Wollstonecraft's unorthodox lifestyle and she became a reviled figure.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Richard Polwhele targeted her in particular in his anonymous long poem *The Unsex'd Females* (1798), a defensive reaction to women's literary self-assertion: Hannah More is Christ to Wollstonecraft's Satan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] His poem was "well known" among the responses to *A Vindication*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Wollstonecraft's ideas became associated with her life story and women writers felt that it was dangerous to mention her in their texts.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Hays, who had previously been a close friend and an outspoken advocate for Wollstonecraft and her *Rights of Woman*, for example, did not include her in the collection of *Illustrious and Celebrated Women* she published in 1803.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Maria Edgeworth specifically distances herself from Wollstonecraft in her novel *Belinda* (1802); she caricatures Wollstonecraft as a radical feminist in the character of Harriet Freke.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] But, like Jane Austen, she does not reject Wollstonecraft's ideas.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Both Edgeworth and Austen argue that women are crucial to the development of the nation; moreover, they portray women as rational beings who should choose companionate marriage.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The negative views towards Wollstonecraft persisted for over a century.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The *Rights of Woman* was not reprinted until the middle of the nineteenth century and it still retained an aura of ill-repute.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] George Eliot wrote "there is in some quarters a vague prejudice against the *Rights of Woman* as in some way or other a reprehensible book, but readers who go to it with this impression will be surprised to find it eminently serious, severely moral, and withal rather heavy".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] The suffragist (i.e. moderate reformer, as opposed to suffragette) Millicent Garrett Fawcett wrote the introduction to the centenary edition of the *Rights of Woman*, cleansing the memory of Wollstonecraft and claiming her as the foremother of the struggle for the vote.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] However, there is some evidence that the *Rights of Woman* may be influencing current feminists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] Miriam Schneir also includes this text in her anthology *Feminism: The Essential Historical Writings*, labelling it as one of the essential feminist works.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/a-vindication-of-the-rights-of-woman] James has one male character reference *Rights of Woman* in reproving another (Darcy) for denying voice to the woman in matters that concern her.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to marry Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Originally launched as **We Are Europeans** (*Siamo Europei*, **SE**), it adopted its current name in November 2019 upon becoming a fully-fledged party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda has described his party as "anti-populist" and "anti-souverainist".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] He also explained that the party's name is a historical reference to the short-lived post-World War II Action Party and an allusion to Carlo Rosselli's "liberal socialism".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] According to Calenda, the party is home to "pure liberals, but also liberal progressives [social liberals, like Calenda] and democratic Catholics [Christian democrats]".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Action was briefly a member of the European Democratic Party and joined the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party in October 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the European Parliament Action's MEPs sat in the Socialists and Democrats group and, later, the liberal Renew Europe group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the European Committee of the Regions, they sit with the Renew Europe CoR Group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the 2013 general election Calenda, who had been active within Luca Cordero di Montezemolo's Future Italy, was an unsuccessful candidate for the centrist Civic Choice (SC) party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] He later served in various capacities (deputy minister, ambassador and minister) in the three governments of the 2013–2018 legislative term.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the aftermath of the 2018 general election, he officially joined the centre-left Democratic Party (PD).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In January 2019, Calenda launched a political manifesto named **We Are Europeans** (*Siamo Europei*), with the aim of creating a joint list composed of the PD and other progressive and pro-Europeanist parties for the upcoming European Parliament election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] His proposal was welcomed by Nicola Zingaretti, then leader of the PD, but rejected by other parties within the centre-left coalition, including More Europe (+E) and Italia in Comune.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the run-up to the election, Zingaretti and Calenda presented a logo for their joint electoral list including a reference to We Are Europeans and the symbol of the Party of European Socialists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Additionally, they also joined with Article One, a left-wing party established in 2017 by splinters from the PD, led by former PD secretary Pier Luigi Bersani.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] The PD–SE joint list gained 22.7% of the vote, coming second after the League.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda, who ran in the North-East constituency, received more than 270,000 votes, thus becoming the most voted candidate of the list, and joined the Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats (S&D) group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In August 2019, tensions grew within the coalition supporting the first government of Giuseppe Conte, leading to the issuing of a motion of no-confidence by the League.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] The party also agreed to keep Conte as the head of the new government, and on 29 August, President Sergio Mattarella re-appointed Conte as Prime Minister, this time at the head of a centre-left coalition.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda strongly opposed the new government, stating that the PD had renounced any representation of the "reformists", and that therefore it became necessary to establish a "liberal-progressive" movement.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda left the PD and on 5 September 2019, while Conte's second government was sworn in, announced the transformation of SE into a full-fledged party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] On 10 September 2019, Matteo Richetti, a prominent PD senator with a Catholic political upbringing and a close associate of former Prime Minister Matteo Renzi, abstained in the vote of confidence on the new government, and subsequently exited the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] He stated that he would join forces with Calenda.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In November 2019, SE was officially transformed into a new party named **Action** (*Azione*), which was organised also at the local level through the so-called "Action Groups" (*Gruppi d'Azione*).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda explained Action's "reformist" nature, while Richetti that "Action would not be a centrist party, but the true progressive pole of the country".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Early donors of the party included Alberto Bombassei and Luciano Cimmino, both former MPs elected with SC.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In August 2020, two members of the Chamber of Deputies joined Action: former minister Enrico Costa, who had earlier left Forza Italia (FI) and a long-time advocate of reforms of the judiciary, and Nunzio Angiola, university professor and former member of the M5S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In November 2020, deputies and senators affiliated with Action formed joint sub-groups in the Mixed Groups together with +E both in the Chamber and in the Senate.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] The sub-group in the Chamber counted four deputies, the one in the Senate three senators.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In March 2021, Carlo Cottarelli, a former director of the International Monetary Fund, was chosen by A, +E, the Italian Republican Party (PRI), the Liberal Democratic Alliance for Italy (ALI) and The Liberals to head of a scientific committee designed to elaborate of a joint political program.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In November 2021, Calenda left the S&D group in the European Parliament, after that it was hinted that the M5S might have joined it, and switched to Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In January 2022, the party formed a federation with +E.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] On 19–20 February 2022, the party held its first congress, during which Calenda was elected secretary, Richetti president, Emma Fattorini (a former senator of the PD) and Giulia Pastorella vice presidents.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda explained that Action would dialogue with all main parties, except the M5S and the Brothers of Italy (FdI), whose leaders were not invited to participate in the congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] A few days before the congress, Barbara Masini had switched from FI.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the coming weeks, senator Leonardo Grimani (ex-PD and ex-IV) and deputies Claudio Pedrazzini, Osvaldo Napoli and Daniela Ruffino (all three ex-FI and ex-Cambiamo!) and Giorgio Trizzino (ex-M5S) joined the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In July 2022, the M5S did not participate in a Senate's confidence vote on a government bill.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Prime Minister Draghi offered his resignation, which was rejected by President Mattarella.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] After a few days, Draghi sought a confidence vote again to secure the government majority supporting his cabinet, while rejecting the proposal put forward by Lega and FI of a new government without the M5S.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In that occasion, the M5S, Lega, FI and FdI did not participate in the vote.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Consequently, Draghi tendered his final resignation to President Mattarella, who dissolved the houses of Parliament, leading to the 2022 general election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda, who also had favoured a Draghi government without the M5S, was very critical of Lega and FI.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the aftermath of Draghi's resignation, senator Andrea Cangini switched from FI to Action.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the event, Calenda hoped that also other leading dissidents of FI, including ministers Mariastella Gelmini and Mara Carfagna, could soon join the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] After Calenda's call, both Gelmini and Carfagna signalled that they would do so and were formally welcomed in the party during a press conference with Calenda.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Contextually, other deputies followed the two ministers out of FI and joined Action.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In early August, Az/+E formed a political pact with the PD, that would give three candidates in single-seat constituencies to Az/+E for every seven candidates given to the PD.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Less than a week later, Calenda announced that he was walking away from the pact because of the parallel alliances that the PD had signed with the Greens and Left Alliance (formed by Green Europe and Italian Left) and Civic Commitment (led by Luigi Di Maio and Bruno Tabacci).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda's decision caused the break-up of the federation with +E, as the latter's leaders wanted to continue their alliance with the PD.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Finally, Action formed a joint electoral list with Matteo Renzi's Italia Viva (IV).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] The joint list obtained 7.8% of the vote.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the aftermath of the election, during a national assembly in Naples, the party elected Carafagna as president with 84% of the delegates' vote, replacing Richetti, who had become the leader in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] The party also approved a path toward a stable federation with IV with 93% of the vote.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] After the election, Renzi frequently clashed with Calenda, leaving the alliance's future uncertain.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In September 2023, Renzi announced that IV would run in the 2024 European Parliament election within a brand new coalition/list named "The Centre".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] This led former minister Elena Bonetti to leave the party in order to seek an alternative alliance with Action.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Also Ettore Rosato, another IV leading member, was critical and seemed interested in joining Action, but, before leaving the party, he was expelled by Renzi.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Subsequently, Bonetti and Rosato launched Populars Europeanists Reformers (PER).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] The pair finally joined Action in January 2024, with Bonetti becoming vice president and Rosato deputy secretary.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Also in January, MP Federica Onori and MEP Fabio Massimo Castaldo switched from the M5S to Action.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In October 2023, having recently exited the European Democratic Party, Action joined the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party (ALDE) as a full member.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In March 2024 Action formed a federative pact with the Italian Republican Party (PRI).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Subsequently, Action formed an alliance also with the European Republicans Movement (MRE).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the run-up of the 2024 European Parliament election, Action presented its "We are Europeans – Action" list.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] This list is composed of eight other parties or groups: NOS, PER, PRI, MRE, Liberal Socialist Association (LS), Liberal Democracy (DL), Reform Popular Civic Platform (PCPR) and Team K.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Contextually, Italia Viva, More Europe, the Italian Socialist Party, the Italian Radicals, the European Liberal Democrats and L'Italia c'è formed an alternative liberal and pro-Europeanist list named "United States of Europe".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] As a result, a minority of More Europe, including its president Federico Pizzarotti, left the party, joined Action and will run in the election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda and Bonetti will stand as candidates in all five constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the run-up of three regional elections scheduled in the fall of 2024, Calenda aligned the party with the centre-left.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] This caused the exit of four senior centre-right figures, namely president Carfagna, deputy secretaries Costa and Gelmini, as well as Giusy Versace.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] The first two were sitting deputies and the other two sitting senators, as a result the party was reduced to 10 deputies and two senators.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Costa re-joined FI, while the other three joined Us Moderates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the run-up to the party's second congress, to be held in March 2025, Calenda was re-elected with 85.8% of the vote by party members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda was challenged by outgoing vice president Pastorella, who was not able to field her candidacy all over the country and was particularly strong in northern Italy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] Calenda proposed a transversal alliance between his party, FI, sectors of the PD and some centrist parties.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In the 2025 regional elections the party did not run as a party, but individual members were elected from centrist joint lists in Aosta Valley and Veneto.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/action-italian-political-party] In February 2026 Elisabetta Gualmini MEP left the PD and joined Action, giving it representation in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The **Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party** (**ALDE Party**) is a liberal European political party composed of national parties from across Europe, mainly active in the European Union.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party is affiliated with Liberal International and a recognised European political party, incorporated as a non-profit association under Belgian law.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] It was founded on 26 March 1976 in Stuttgart as a confederation of national political parties under the name "Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe" and renamed "European Liberals and Democrats" (ELD) in 1977 and "European Liberal Democrats and Reformists" (ELDR) in 1986.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 30 April 2004, the ELDR was reformed as an official European party, the "European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party" (ELDR Party).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Prior to the 2004 European election, the European party had been represented through its own group, the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party Group (ELDR) Group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2024, ALDE Party is represented in European Union institutions, with 51 MEPs and five members of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Of the 27 EU member states, there are two with ALDE-affiliated Prime Ministers: Kristen Michal (Estonian Reform Party) in Estonia and Alexander De Croo (Open VLD) in Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE Party members are also in governments in ten other EU member states: Cyprus, France, Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Ireland, Luxembourg, Lithuania, Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Charles Michel, former Belgian prime minister, was the president of the European Council until December 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE's think tank is the European Liberal Forum, led by Jan-Christoph Oetjen MEP, and gathers 46 member organisations.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The youth wing of ALDE is the European Liberal Youth (LYMEC), which is predominantly based upon youth and student liberal organisations but contains also a small number of individual members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2011, ALDE Party became the first pan-European party to create the status of individual membership.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Since then, between 1000 and close to 3000 members (the numbers fluctuate annually) maintained direct membership in the ALDE Party from several EU countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Over 40 coordinators mobilised liberal ideas, initiatives and expertise across the continent under the leadership of the steering committee, which was first chaired by Julie Cantalou.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party took a step further in the direction of becoming a truly pan-European party when granting voting rights to individual members' delegates at the Party Congress.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Individual membership was eventually discontinued in 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2025, the Alliance was declared an undesirable organization in Russia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Pan-European liberalism has a long history dating back to the foundation of Liberal International in April 1947.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 26 March 1976, the Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe was established in Stuttgart.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The founding parties of the federation were the Free Democratic Party of Germany, Radical Party of France, Venstre of Denmark, Italian Liberal Party, Dutch People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and Democratic Party of Luxembourg.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Observer members joining later in 1976 were the Danish Social Liberal Party, French Radical Party of the Left and Independent Republicans, British Liberal Party, and Italian Republican Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 1977, the federation was renamed European Liberals and Democrats, in 1986, European Liberal Democrats and Reformists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 10 November 2012, the ELDR Party adopted the name of the alliance between the two parties, to match the parliamentary group and the alliance.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 12 June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by a new enlarged group, Renew Europe, which primarily consists of ALDE and EDP member parties and France's La République En Marche!
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As a registered European political party, ALDE is entitled to European public funding, which it has received continuously since 2004.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of European public funding received by ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In line with the Regulation on European political parties and European political foundations, ALDE also raises private funds to co-finance its activities.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2025, European parties must raise at least 10% of their reimbursable expenditure from private sources, while the rest can be covered using European public funding.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of contributions and donations received by the ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of January 2026 ALDE party had 55 full member and ten affiliated parties from EU and non-EU countries.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Only delegates from full members of the ALDE Party and its youth wing LYMEC, together with the delegates of the ALDE Party Supporters and ALDE Party Bureau members, are permitted to vote at the ALDE Congress and Council.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Affiliated member parties have non-voting delegates.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE also includes a number of individual members.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] For many years, ALDE had the largest number of individual members of all European parties; however, this membership was discontinued with only one individual member remaining as of 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As most other European parties, it has not sought to develop mass individual membership.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of individual membership of ALDE since 2019.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The party's ideological character is contested by political scientists, although it is widely considered to be populist in nature.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] After being formed predominantly as an anti-corruption vehicle, the party has at different times been considered centrist, liberal, conservative, right-wing, social democratic, or centre-left, by different commentators, leading to a further characterisation as a syncretic or catch-all party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Since the 2024 European Parliament election, the party has positioned itself to the right, co-founding Patriots for Europe, a group in the European Parliament that is made up of Eurosceptic parties that primarily adhere to right-wing populism and national conservatism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In December 2025, ANO formed a majority coalition government in the Czech Republic with Freedom and Direct Democracy and Motorists for Themselves.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The party's founding was preceded by interventions from leader and founder Andrej Babiš commenting on systemic corruption in the Czech political system.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] It was established as an association in November 2011 under the name **Action of Dissatisfied Citizens** (Czech: *Akce nespokojených občanů*), and formally registered as a political party in the Czech Republic under the name **ANO 2011** on 11 May 2012.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In the 2013 parliamentary election held on 25 and 26 October, ANO won 18.7% of the vote and 47 seats in the Chamber of Deputies, finishing in second place behind the Social Democrats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 29 January 2014, the Cabinet of Social Democrat Prime Minister Bohuslav Sobotka was sworn in, with ANO and the Christian and Democratic Union – Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-ČSL) as junior coalition partners.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 24–25 May 2014, ANO came first in the 2014 European Parliament election, winning 16.13% of votes and four seats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The party joined the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe (ALDE) group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 10 September 2014, ANO member Věra Jourová was named European Commissioner for Justice, Consumers and Gender Equality in the Juncker Commission.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 21 November 2014, ANO was granted full membership of the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party (ALDE Party) at a congress in Lisbon.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In the 2014 senate and municipal elections held on 10–11 October 2014, ANO won four seats in the Senate, and was the largest party in 8 of the 10 biggest cities in the Czech Republic, including Prague.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The party took mayoral offices in the three largest cities (Prague, Brno and Ostrava), and Adriana Krnáčová became the first female mayor of Prague.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] However, many of the municipal coalitions involving ANO subsequently dissolved due to disagreements within the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In the run-up to the 2016 Czech regional elections, Babiš started *Babiš's Cafe*, a television show consisting of interviews with Babiš by Pavla Charvátová, as well as viewers' questions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Two parties split from ANO citing a lack of democracy and discussion within the party: Change for People and PRO 2016 (English: FOR 2016), the latter of which was joined by numerous local councillors and mayors from ANO.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Some of those leaving attributed their departure to conflicts related to candidate selection, alleging that the main criterion for candidates to regional councils was loyalty, rather than ability.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO also lost one MP in July 2016 when Kristýna Zelienková left the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO won the 2016 regional elections and the first round of the 2016 senate election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The party came first in nine regions and second in the other four regions; its victory in South Bohemia was particularly unexpected.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO emerged from the election with five governors, one of whom, the Karlovy Vary Governor Jana Vildumetzová, became chair of the Association of Regions.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Three ANO candidates were elected in the second round of the senate election, considered a disappointing result for the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 11 October 2017, MEP Pavel Telička announced his departure from the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Another MEP, Petr Ježek, left ANO on 23 January 2018.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 20–21 October 2017, ANO won the 2017 Czech parliamentary election with 29.6% of the vote.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO formed the short-lived first Babiš government with independent ministers on 13 December 2017, failing a vote of confidence on 16 January 2018.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 12 July 2018 the second Babiš government was formed, with the Social Democrats participating as the junior coalition partner.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The cabinet received external support from the Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In the 2018 Czech municipal elections, the party again came first, but lost its mayoral offices of Prague and Brno to the Czech Pirate Party and the Civic Democratic Party (ODS), respectively.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In May 2019, ANO came first in the 2019 European Parliament election with 21.2% of the vote, returning six MEPs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In the 2020 Cezch regional elections, the party lost two governors' offices, but joined various regional coalitions, forming a cordon sanitaire against the Communist Party and the far-right Freedom and Direct Democracy.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO went into the 2021 Czech parliamentary election leading in opinion polls, but finished second behind the Spolu coalition, though with a higher number of seats.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Following the 2024 European Parliament election on 21 June 2024, the party unilaterally withdrew from both the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party and Renew Europe group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 30 June 2024, Babiš launched the Patriots for Europe, along with Prime Minister of Hungary and Fidesz party leader Viktor Orbán and Freedom Party of Austria leader Herbert Kickl.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Patriots for Europe reached the criteria for becoming a European Parliament group on 8 July.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO won the 2025 Czech parliamentary election and subsequently entered negotiations to form a government with Freedom and Direct Democracy and Motorists for Themselves.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO negotiated a coalition with the far-right Freedom and Direct Democracy (SPD) and the national-conservative Motorists for Themselves (AUTO).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The government was sworn in on 15 December 2025.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 24 January 2026, Babiš was re-elected unopposed as ANO leader, with 196 out of 209 votes (94%).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO's political position is debated among politicians and political scientists.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Political scientists historically placed ANO in the centre, or centre-right, while in latter years the party focused on left-leaning voters and promoted policies described as centre-left, or even left-wing, until 2024.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Bne IntelliNews evaluated ANO as taking a right-wing direction after it left Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party (ALDE Party) and Renew Europe in 2024, while others have described the party as conservative, centre-right populist, and right-wing populist.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Babiš himself stated in an interview in 2014 that ANO was "a right-wing party with social empathy".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO's ideology was widely described as simply populist until 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO 2011 has also been characterised as technocratic, techno-populist, syncretic, and a big tent or catch-all party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Given its former membership in the ALDE Party and Renew Europe, which mostly comprise liberal parties, ANO has also historically been described as liberal, conservative-liberal, centre-right liberal, liberal-conservative, and liberal-populist.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Ideologically, the party had similarities with the Christian and Democratic Union – Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-ČSL), as well as the now-defunct Public Affairs.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Additionally, ANO, or more specifically Babiš, has been compared to Silvio Berlusconi from Forza Italia or US president Donald Trump.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Multiple candidates that were elected for the party have left ANO since 2014, asserting that it is no longer a liberal party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] After the 2017 Czech parliamentary election, ANO formed a minority government with support from the Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSČM), ending the cordon sanitaire against them.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] KSČM also endorsed Babiš in the 2023 Czech presidential election.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In early 2023, many from the party leadership signalled the party's shift towards conservatism, both socially and fiscally, as Babiš was cooperating with Hungarian prime minister Viktor Orbán and the Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC).
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The agenda for the party's 2023 conference specifically stated Babiš to be a "conservative leader".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The ANO leadership has also criticised the centre-right Civic Democratic Party (ODS), claiming that it is no longer right-wing but is instead in the "progressive camp" with the Czech Pirate Party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO generally opposes economic liberalism.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In some spheres, such as tax policy, Babiš introduced centre-left elements to the movement's politics, including the abolition of the partial tax exemption for self-employed persons and restoration of the partial tax exemption for employed pensioners.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] He also introduced a proposal to increase school teacher wages by 2.5%, as opposed to his ministry's original proposal for a 1% increase.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In the area of healthcare, Babiš has criticised public health insurance companies for their level of spending.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO is generally described as a Eurosceptic or a soft Eurosceptic party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Daniel Kaiser of Echo24 called the party's stance towards the EU "Euro-opportunism".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Babiš stated that ANO opposes the Czech Republic's adoption of the Euro, further European integration, immigration quotas, and "Brussels bureaucracy".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Babiš stated later that he was open to adopting the euro once the Czech Republic had a balanced budget.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] He also argued in favour of closer ties with Germany and said the Czech Republic was already ready to sign the Fiscal Compact treaty at the time of the interview in 2014.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Although ANO initially supported military aid to Ukraine following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, by June 2022, Babiš was calling for an end to Czech military aid, stating that the objective of preventing a Russian takeover of the entirety of Ukraine had been achieved.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] During his 2023 Czech presidential election campaign, Babiš advocated for negotiations between Russia and Ukraine to end the Russo-Ukrainian War, criticising his opponent's absolute support for Ukraine.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Babiš has also opposed potential Ukrainian EU membership, describing it as a "complete catastrophe".
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In 2026, Babiš confirmed that the ammunition initiative for Ukraine would continue, having previously criticised the scheme as opaque and called for it to be audited or scrapped.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO has a highly centralised organisational structure.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The strongest position is that of the chair, who acts independently when representing the party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The highest body of ANO is its National Assembly, which meets at least once every two years.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Other national offices include membership of the Party Committee and the Bureau.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Regional assemblies can elect their own chairs; however, they must be approved by the Bureau before they can take office.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The Bureau also approves all candidates for elections.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] For these reasons, and considering Babiš's businesses, it has been described as a business-firm party.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] The Institute for Politics and Society, founded in October 2014, is a think tank affiliated with ANO.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In March 2015, journalist Jan Macháček became the chairman of the institute.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Young ANO, the party's youth wing, was established on 1 May 2015, with Kateřina Reiblová as the inaugural leader.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] She resigned in July 2015, with Babiš stating that she was disgusted by the media.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] She was replaced by Tomáš Krátký, who was elected as chair during the organisation's first convention.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO joined the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe (ALDE) group in June 2014, and the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party (ALDE party) in November 2014.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] ANO was described variously as "a headache" and a "thorn in the side" for the liberal group.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] Other members of these groups criticised Babiš and questioned his commitment to the ethos of these organisations due to Babiš being invited to, attending, and speaking at the Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC) in Budapest, Hungary, in May 2023.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] During the 2023 Slovak parliamentary election, Babiš expressed support for Robert Fico's Smer–SD and Peter Pellegrini's Hlas-SD in Slovakia, over ALDE member Progressive Slovakia.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] In June 2024, ANO unilaterally resigned from both the ALDE party and its affiliated Renew Europe group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party/ano-political-party] On 30 June 2024, ANO, the Freedom Party of Austria and Hungarian party Fidesz launched the new group Patriots for Europe, which was officially formed on 8 July, replacing the Identity and Democracy group at the European political level.
